A term referring to corrupt [[Latin America]]n governments (largely in [[Central America]]) that allow foreign business to run their country.  United Fruit was one of the first to use this tactic in exporting bananas from [[Guatemala]].  Prior to 1870, bananas were unknown in the United States. 

''A BANANA REPUBLIC'' — a form of government where cronyism, deceit and cash payments substitute for more [[democratic]] forms of political influence, like debate and balloting; a one-issue political body in a certain political subdivision.  Thus the term for Miami where ousting Castro is more important to local politicians, and their counterparts in Washington, than education, roads, clean water, etc.